						<div class="left-col">
							<div class="paragraph1">
								<p class="bold">How do I start playing?</p>

								<p>Once you have chosen a table, a window will popup and the game will load. Available
									seats are the square panels showing 'Join'. Clicking any of these squares will
									reserve that seat for you whilst you select how much you want to bring to the table
									in the Buy-In menu. Once you have selected an amount to buy-in with, you will be
									placed in your selected seat and the camera will adjust your position to the central
									seat, so all other players are around you. You cannot play Texas Hold'em on more
									than one seat per table. </p>
							</div>
							<div class="paragraph2">
								<p>The game will start as long as there are at least 2 players at the table. If you join
									whilst a game is in progress, you can opt to pay the big blind early and join the
									game in the next round by checking the 'Post BB Early to Join' button, otherwise
									you'll have to wait until it's your turn to post the big blind to join.</p>
							</div>
						</div>
					</div>
					<div class="block3 font-compnonlogged-2 float-left-col">
						<h4 class="font-how-to-play-headline drop bold">TEXAS HOLD'EM POKER RULES</h4>

						<div>
							<div class="left-col">
								<div class="paragraph1">
									<p>A player is assigned as the dealer, and this is indicated by the dealer button
										(D) placed on the table in front of that player. The dealer button moves
										clockwise around the table for each game.</p>
								</div>
								<div class="paragraph2">
									<p>The 2 players to the left of the dealer post blind bets. The player directly to
										the dealer's left puts out the 'Small Blind' (SB), while the next player to the
										left puts out the 'Big Blind' (BB). Blind bets have to be placed at the start of
										each game, and before any cards are dealt. If any player opts to sit out or
										fails to make an action when it's their turn to post a 'blind', they will remain
										sitting out until the 'I'm Back' button is pressed. To rejoin the game the
										player must either wait until it's his/her turn to post the big blind or select
										the 'Pay Missed Blinds' button to join earlier than that.</p>
								</div>
								<div class="paragraph2">
									<p>After the blinds are in place two 'pocket cards' are dealt to each player face
										down, and only you will be able to see what your cards are. The action falls on
										the player to the left of the big blind, who can either call, raise or fold.
										Betting continues clockwise around the table. Each player has a certain amount
										of time to take their turn, indicated by the timer around your picture. If any
										player fails to take their turn in time, they will automatically fold their
										hand.</p>
								</div>
								<div class="paragraph2">
									<p>After all players have had a chance to call and bet, the first 3 of the community
										cards are dealt face up in the centre of the table, which are called the flop.
										Community cards are used by everyone playing on the table in combination with
										their own cards to make the best hand. Following the flop, another round of
										betting starts from the player to the dealer's left.</p>
								</div>
								<div class="paragraph2">
									<p>The fourth community card is then dealt face up next to the flop. This is called
										the turn. Another round of betting occurs before the fifth and final community
										card is dealt, which is called the river.</p>
								</div>
								<div class="paragraph2">
									<p>A final round of betting occurs, and then the remaining players show their cards
										in the 'showdown'. The person with the best 5 card hand by combining their
										pocket cards with the community cards wins.</p>
								</div>
								<div class="paragraph2">
									<p>If 2 or more players have the same winning hands, the pot is split equally
										between them.</p>
								</div>
								<div class="paragraph2">
									<p class="bold2">Buy-Ins and Bettings</p>

									<p>Yazino currently only offers No Limit poker. However other types are planned to
										be added in due course.</p>
								</div>
								<div class="paragraph2">
									<p>No Limit games have a minimum and maximum buy-in, which is the minimum and
										maximum amount of chips you can bring to the table when you take your seat. When
										you join a seat, it is reserved for 30 seconds to allow you to decide how much
										you want to buy-in with.</p>
								</div>
								<div class="paragraph2">
									<p>During a betting round in a 'No Limit' game, there is no limit to the maximum bet
										or raise that you can make; as long as it's within the balance you have at the
										table at that time. There is a minimum bet which is equivalent to the big
										blind.</p>
								</div>
								<div class="paragraph2">
									<p>Minimum raises must be at least as much as the previous bet or raise in the same
										betting round. If you call a bet but don't have enough chips to cover it, you
										will go 'All-In' and the pot will be split so you can only win whatever your
										share of the total pot is.</p>
								</div>
								<div class="paragraph2">
									<p class="bold">Time-outs</p>

									<p>Player's will be marked as 'Away' if their timer runs out before making an
										action. Whilst 'Away' they will still place blinds but automatically fold their
										hands. Normal play can be resumed by pressing the 'I'm Back' button. If any
										player stays 'Away' for 3 consecutive hands, they will automatically lose their
										seat.</p>
								</div>
								<div class="paragraph2">
									<p class="bold">Card Deck and Hand Ranks</p>

									<p>A single 52 card deck is used in Texas Hold'em. All suits have an equal value,
										and aces are the highest card, and 2's the lowest.</p>
								</div>
								<div class="paragraph2">
									<p><span class="bold">Texas Hold'em rules</span> for hand ranks are the same as in
										any other version of poker. Your hand is made up using the 5 best cards out of
										the 2 pocket cards you have plus the 5 community cards on the table. The value
										of 'Your Hand' is displayed above the dealer chat on the table, and the rankings
										of each category can be viewed by pressing the '?' button on the table. Learning
										poker hand ranks will prove very useful while playing Texas Hold'em.</p>
								</div>
								<div class="paragraph2">
									<p>The minimum buy-in for the game is 10 big blinds and the maximum is 50 big
										blinds.</p>
								</div>
								<div class="paragraph2">
									<p>Malfunction voids all pays and plays.</p>
								</div>
